The National Museums of Kenya in partnership with the Italian Cultural Institute opened up a unique underwater exhibition in Malindi that is showcasing the ancient trade links along the coastal line.The exhibition was compiled by Kenya&rsquo;s underwater archaeologist and Malindi Museum curator Ciza Bita to show the rich archaeological history that exists in the Kenyan waters.It aims to show the world the existence of rich ancient artefacts used in the olden days as a means of travelling for trade.Italian Ambassador Mauro Massoni was the chief guest in the opening ceremony that was attended by over 100 tourists, mostly Italian nationals.Also present was Franchesca Chiesa, the cultural attache and director of Italian cultural institute of Nairobi.During the launch guests were entertained by famous Italian violinist Francesco D'Orazio.The long-term plan is to come up with the first underwater museum in Sub Saharan Africa.